# TanStack Start Patterns

You are a TanStack Start expert focused on leveraging the full power of the framework. Follow these guidelines:

## Project Structure

```sh
app/
├── api.ts                  # Root API configuration
├── components/             # Shared components
│   ├── ui/                # UI components
│   └── features/          # Feature components
├── lib/                   # Shared utilities
│   ├── client/           # Client-only code
│   ├── server/           # Server-only code
│   └── shared/           # Shared code
├── routes/                # File-based routes
│   ├── __root.tsx        # Root layout
│   ├── api/              # API routes
│   │   ├── auth/         # Auth-related endpoints
│   │   │   └── $.ts     # Auth handler (catch-all)
│   │   └── send.ts      # Email sending endpoint
│   ├── _public/          # Public routes
│   │   ├── route.tsx    # Public layout
│   │   ├── index.tsx    # Landing page
│   │   └── about.tsx    # About page
│   ├── _auth/           # Auth routes
│   │   ├── route.tsx    # Auth layout
│   │   ├── signin.tsx   # Sign in page
│   │   └── signup.tsx   # Sign up page
│   └── _app/            # Protected routes
│       ├── route.tsx    # App layout with auth guard
│       ├── dashboard/   # Dashboard feature
│       │   ├── route.tsx# Dashboard layout
│       │   └── index.tsx# Dashboard page
│       └── users/       # Users feature
│           ├── route.tsx# Users layout
│           ├── index.tsx# Users list
│           └── [id].tsx # User detail
├── client.tsx            # Client entry
├── router.tsx            # Router config
└── ssr.tsx              # Server entry
```

## Server Functions

### Naming Convention

- Always prefix with `$`
- Use camelCase after the `$` prefix
- Follow verb-noun format:

  ```typescript
  // ✅ Correct server function naming
  $getUser;
  $updateProfile;
  $deletePost;
  $createComment;

  // ❌ Incorrect server function naming
  getUser;
  $User_Update;
  $post_delete;
  createComment;
  ```

### Organization

```typescript
// ✅ Proper server function organization
// features/users/api/index.ts
export const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' })
  .handler(async ({ params }) => {
    // Implementation
  });

export const $updateUser = createServerFn({ method: 'POST' })
  .validator((data) => userSchema.parse(data))
  .handler(async ({ data }) => {
    // Implementation
  });

// ❌ Poor server function organization
// Don't mix with component logic
function UserProfile() {
  const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' });
  return <div>...</div>;
}
```

## API Routes

### Directory Structure

```sh
app/routes/
├── api/                # API routes directory
│   ├── auth/          # Auth-related endpoints
│   │   └── $.ts      # Auth handler (catch-all)
│   └── send.ts       # Email sending endpoint
└── // ... other route files
```

### Implementation

```typescript
// routes/api/auth/$.ts - Catch-all auth handler
export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/auth/$')({
  GET: ({ request }) => {
    return auth.handler(request);
  },
  POST: ({ request }) => {
    return auth.handler(request);
  },
});

// routes/api/send.ts - Feature-specific endpoint
export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/send')({
  POST: async ({ request }) => {
    const { to, template, data } = await request.json();
    return resend.emails.send({
      to,
      template,
      data,
    });
  },
});
```

### Route Organization

1. File Structure:

   - Use `__root.tsx` for root layout
   - Use `_public/`, `_auth/`, etc. for route grouping
   - Use `route.tsx` for layouts and guards
   - Use `index.tsx` for page components
   - Use `[param].tsx` for dynamic routes
   - Use `$.ts` for catch-all API handlers

